{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654880"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:56:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:56:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18640"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18640"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.07,0.62,0.17,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78558"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11372"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63900"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6905"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26919"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78558"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior rectus sheath forms an important part of the anterior abdominal wall. Its composition varies above and below the arcuate line.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation of the anterior rectus sheath above the arcuate line?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["All three lateral abdominal muscle aponeuroses","External oblique aponeurosis alone","External oblique and internal oblique aponeuroses","External oblique and transversus abdominis aponeuroses","Internal oblique and transversus abdominis aponeuroses"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAbove the arcuate line, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eexternal oblique and internal oblique aponeuroses\u003C/strong\u003E form the anterior rectus sheath. Specifically, the external oblique aponeurosis and the anterior layer of the internal oblique aponeurosis fuse to create this structure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal oblique and transversus abdominis aponeuroses\u003C/strong\u003E - The external oblique contributes to the anterior sheath, while the transversus abdominis forms part of the posterior sheath above the arcuate line\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll three lateral abdominal muscle aponeuroses\u003C/strong\u003E - This arrangement only occurs below the arcuate line\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal oblique aponeurosis alone\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incomplete as the anterior layer of internal oblique aponeurosis also contributes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal oblique and transversus abdominis aponeuroses\u003C/strong\u003E - The internal oblique contributes to the anterior sheath, not the transversus abdominis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBelow the arcuate line, all three aponeuroses (external oblique, internal oblique and transversus abdominis) pass anterior to the rectus abdominis muscle, leaving no posterior rectus sheath.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The anterior rectus sheath above the arcuate line is formed by the external oblique aponeurosis and anterior layer of internal oblique aponeurosis.","Below the arcuate line, all three lateral abdominal muscle aponeuroses pass anterior to the rectus abdominis muscle.","The arcuate line is located approximately midway between the umbilicus and pubic symphysis."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63900"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18640"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63900"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T13:55:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T13:55:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11372"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78558"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Ga